<subSubSection id="90F1BD3D8321FEC0C8D62597989BCFFD" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" type="diversity">
<paragraph id="C60929FDB746766CA9E683814B2A41CF" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">
<pageBreakToken id="46D1D6393A3BA34EC0AAFBF753212C85" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" start="start">Diversity</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F8EFFEFCBFA915E0B1169109ABB5DEC8" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">
About 120 species (Lorenz 2005: 438-439), mainly in the tropical regions, arrayed in five genera. Only one endemic species (
<taxonomicName id="BB34533EC48B78644A8E4252620AA1FE" baseAuthorityName="LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1853" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Perigona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallipennis">
<emphasis id="CB7CA957916A46B640F85B9E35110DEF" italics="true" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">Perigona pallipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is found in North America and one in Europe (
<taxonomicName id="FEA7389FE1088BA2D5207375747525F2" authorityName="Assmann" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Galiciotyphlotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weberi">
<emphasis id="258114FD9DA2136C8FFE983DA82045BE" italics="true" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">Galiciotyphlotes weberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Assmann from northwestern Spain).
</paragraph>
